    <h1>Understanding the German kita system</h1>

    <h2>What is a kita?</h2>
    <p>In Germany, school starts at the age of 6. If parents are looking for children day care before their children reach that age, the most frequent solution are the <i>Kindertagesstätte</i>, more commonly known as kitas.</p>
    <p>Each kita is divided into two parts. The first one is the Kinderkrippe and takes care of children below the age of 3. But even if many kitas claim to accept children as young as 8 weeks old on their website, most of them are reluctant to have small babies and prefer to have children that are at least 1 year old. For children between the age of 3 and 6, the Kindergarten is where they will be cared for.</p>
    <p>Kitas come in all shapes and forms and parents should pay attention to certain elements before applying. For instance, each kita puts an emphasis on different aspects of education, among which are: languages (some kitas are officially bilingual or even multilingual), religion, integration, nature... Some also follow a certain educational concept such as Montessori or Waldorf.</p>

