    <h2>The Kita Gutschein</h2>
    <p>German states all have different regulations concerning children day care. Berlin offers a free day care system from which parents can benefit through a <i>Gutschein</i> (voucher). This Gutschein can be valid for <i>Halbstags</i> (4 to 5 hours a day), <i>Teilzeit</i> (5 to 7 hours a day), <i>Ganztags</i> (7 to 9 hours a day) or <i>Erweitere Ganztags</i> (more than 9 hours a day).</p>
    <p>The Gutschein are provided by the <i>Jugendamt</i>, which will ask from parents their need of day care. However, if the child is at least 1 year old, a Teilzeit Gutschein will be provided regardless of the parents' professional situation. Moreover, having access to day care passed the age of 1 is officially a right and legal actions can be pushed forward if the parents have not managed to find a spot.</p>

    <h2>The different types of children day care</h2>
    <p>Even if kitas are the most typical type of day care, finding a spot can be complicated, but alternatives exist.</p>
    <p>The <i>Tagesmütter</i> or <i>Tageseltern</i> (German equivalent to nannies) can take care of around 3 to 5 children at a time. Sometimes they pair up to be able to look after 6 to 10 kids. They accept children from a young age, but do not look after children older than 3 - parents will then need to find a kita for the remaining years before school.</p>
    <p>The <i>EKT - Eltern Initiativ Kindertagesstätte</i> are kitas that are run collectively by parents and carers. They can also be referred to as <i>Kinderladen</i>. They are not as big as kitas, which can be beneficial to the children, and parents have a certain control over the way the kita operates. But they do require some extra time from the parents (cleaning the premises, preparing lunch) and tend to have shorter opening hours. They are not recommended for families where both parents work full-time.</p>


